The United States had a number of banking houses or trading houses where they were able to establish a line of credit. 

- BW2:517: SecNav sends [Edward Preble]() $30,000, with this reasoning: "You would otherwise in all probability be constrained to draw bills to a great disadvantage so long as the present war continues in Europe. This sum by being judiciously distributed among the squadron, may render it unnecessary for the Commanders to draw on either of the places where a credit is deposited for them, or it will so far abridge the amount of their drafts, that no considerable loss in the Exchange will be experienced" (22 August 1803)